                                                                                                                                 2                                                                                      More teeth to fight Maoists
          OUR SPECIAL CORRESPONDENT                          Naveen: Happy at Centres pledge                                  
	Bhubaneswar, Jan. 22: The Centre has promised the state five more battalions of central paramilitary forces and two helicopters for anti-Maoist operations.        
	Union home minister P. Chidambaram announced this at a meeting with the chief ministers of three Maoist-affected states  Orissa, Chhattisgarh and Maharashtra  in Raipur today.        
	He assured Orissa five more battalions of central paramilitary forces and two helicopters to fight out the rebels, chief minister Naveen Patnaik told reporters here this afternoon after returning from Raipur.        
	Besides Naveen, todays meeting was attended by his Chhattisgarh counterpart Raman Singh and Maharashtra deputy chief minister home minister R.R. Patil.        
	Naveen said he had put forth demands for construction of more roads and bridges, particularly in border areas where Maoist activities were going on. He also demanded funding of Vijaywada-Ranchi highway, which passes through most of Maoist-hit districts.        
	The meeting was fruitful, Naveen said, expressing satisfaction over the deliberations and the support assured by the Centre.         
	Asked as to when the joint operations by the three states would start, Naveen said: Let the five battalions of central paramilitary forces assured by the Centre come. Then only the picture will be clear.        
	Replying to a question as to why Jharkhand chief minister was not invited to todays meeting, he said another meeting of chief ministers or home ministers of Jharkhand and Bengal would be held soon.        
	On the measures taken to handle the Orissa bandh called by Maoists on Republic Day and a two-day economic blockade on January 25-26, the chief minister said: We will ensure that the bandh passes off peacefully. Police will remain vigilant.        
	Outlawed CPI(Maoist) has called a state-wide bandh on Republic Day and economic blockade on January 25-26 in protest against state repression and demanding release of Subhashree, alias Saswati, alias Mili, the wife of top Maoist leader Sabyasachi Panda.                                                                                                                                                          
